04/02/2004
ATHENS, Greece -- Gianna Angelopoulo-Daskalaki, the chief organiser of the 2004 Summer Olympics, told reporters on Tuesday (3 February) that "everything humanly possible to provide the world with safe and secure Games" has been done. "We have to remain vigilant and sensitive to every single change in the atmosphere," she said. Angelopoulos praised those involved in the construction effort for making up for the initial delays. "Everything is on schedule ... The international sports community is thrilled with the progress we have made."
In other news, Greek Public Order Minister Giorgos Floridis praised co-operation with Russia in addressing some of the possible threats. He met with Moscow's chiefs of domestic security and intelligence about chemical and biological decontamination. (Reuters, AP - 03/02/04)
